==English==

===Etymology===
First attested around 1472. From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|absurdite}},<ref name=RHD>{{R:RHCD|page=7}}</ref> then from either {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|absurdité}}, or from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|la|absurditas||dissonance, incongruity}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|absurdus}} {{suffix|la||itas|gloss2=quality, state, degree|nocat=1}}.<ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976|page=8}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=10}}</ref> Equivalent to {{suffix|en|absurd|ity}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/əbˈsɜːd.ɪ.ti/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/æbˈsɝd.ɪ.ti/|/æbˈzɝd.ɪ.ti/|/əbˈsɝd.ɪ.ti/|/əbˈzɝd.ɪ.ti/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|absurdities}}

# {{lb|en|countable}} That which is absurd; an absurd action; a [[logical]] [[contradiction]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 15<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=His travels were full of '''absurdities'''.|author=Johnson}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The quality of being absurd or [[inconsistent]] with [[obvious]] truth, reason, or sound judgment. {{defdate|First attested in the early 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=The '''absurdity''' of the actual idea of an infinite number.|author=[[w:John Locke|John Locke]]}}
#* {{RQ:Schuster Hepaticae|volume=V|page=viii|text=Neither [Jones]{{...}} nor I (in 1966) could conceive of reducing our "science" to the ultimate '''absurdity''' of reading Finnish newspapers almost a century and a half old in order to establish "priority."}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|rare}} [[dissonance|Dissonance]]. {{defdate|Attested from around 1350 to 1470 until the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

